humb/s03tyr5yzeeg2xr7uij0.jpg"}, {"id": 12871, "url": "//images.igdb.com/igdb/image/upload/t_thumb/xuspvieg9bzvuct4zgee.jpg"}, {"id": 13371, "url": "//images.igdb.com/igdb/image/upload/t_thumb/i7hp6vuz2kz5tgu1w6yx.jpg"}, {"id": 15599, "url": "//images.igdb.com/igdb/image/upload/t_thumb/euteaq8rbfqahujkvxlv.jpg"}, {"id": 17185, "url": "//images.igdb.com/igdb/image/upload/t_thumb/psda9t2yxavlmnum5ugs.jpg"}, {"id": 1054335, "url": "//images.igdb.com/igdb/image/upload/t_thumb/scmlj3.jpg"}], "slug": "arkanoid", "storyline": "The player controls the \"Vaus\", a space vessel that acts as the game's \"paddle\" which prevents a ball from falling from the playing field, attempting to bounce it against a number of bricks. The ball striking a brick causes the brick to disappear. When all the bricks are gone, the player goes to the next level, where another pattern of bricks appears. There are a number of variations (bricks that have to be hit multiple times, flying enemy ships, etc.) and power-up capsules to enhance the Vaus (expand the Vaus, multiply the number of balls, equip a laser cannon, break directly to the next level, etc.), but the gameplay remains the same.\n\nAt round 33, the final stage, the player will take on the game's boss, \"DOH\", a head resembling moai. Once a player reaches round 33, he must defeat DOH with his remaining extra lives because there are no continues on the final round.", "summary": "Arkanoid is an arcade game developed by Taito in 1986. It expanded upon Atari's Breakout games of the 1970s by adding power-ups, different types of bricks, and a variety of level layouts. The title refers to a doomed \"mothership\" from which the player's ship, the Vaus, escapes.", "themes": [{"id": 1, "name": "Action"}, {"id": 18, "name": "Science fiction"}], "url": "https://www.igdb.com/games/arkanoid", "videos": [{"id": 89714, "name": "Gameplay Video", "video_id": "0AVHfgCMIQ8", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0AVHfgCMIQ8", "title": "Arkanoid (World, old